			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I am not sure how many of you have been following the story of the Shiavo case (<a href="http://www.cnn.com/2005/LAW/03/24/schiavo/index.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">HERE is the CNN version of it</a>)
<br />

<br />
I know that there are folks on both side of the fence. Folks have taken a stand on the morality issues, some have taken a stand on the tactics used on both sides, some who have taken a stand on whether the government should have intervened. Some are even involved in the Vaticans position on the case. All of this is, in my opinion, superfluous bullshit.
<br />

<br />
The Florida law, in which this whole case hinges, was, also in my opinion, put in place for terminally ill and medically brain dead patients, who can not make the decision for themselves whether or not to be kept alive by artificial means. The ward, in this case, falls to the husband to make this decision. Because the law was so broadly written, and if I might add, so crappily written, that this power of decision was granted in a situation where I don't believe he should have the power to do so. This is the part that pisses me off so bad.
<br />

<br />
Setting aside all the extra BS surrounding the case, the bottom line is his claim that she stated to him that she would not want to live in a vegetative state, and her parents who don't believe him and wish to care for her until she dies from natural causes.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">His position</span>
<br />
He has stated over and over that at one time, while watching some movie where the actor was in an accident, she told him that she would "not want to live like that". Because of this assertion, he is exercising his right, under Florida law, to end her life. We will never know if she really made this claim or not, because, apparently he is the only one who heard this. We are supposed to believe him. But what burns my ass is that it doesn't matter if we believe him or not, he has the power to take this action based on the fubar Florida law.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Parent's position</span>
<br />
They simple want to take care of their daughter. They have offered complete monetary responsibility, as well as all future care for Terry. On the surface, you may think that he really is trying to carry out Terry's wishes. But, if he cares so much, why has he shacked up with another woman and had two children already. There is even speculation as to his real motivation, one being life insurance, the other being a possibility that he was somehow involved in her accident. This raises enough doubt in my mind. Yet, he is standing fast, and I just don't get it.
<br />

<br />
When all is said and done, the jackass is probably going to win, and Terry is going to die an agonizing death (comparable, imo, to drowning or burning to death). The whole thing just pisses me off to no end. I just pray that it was, indeed, her wish not to be kept alive because, obviously, the courts nor her jackass husband give a shit about her.
<br />

<br />

<br />
PS If this subject is not appropiete for these forums, I completely understand....I just needed to vent.<br />_________________<br /><span style="font-style: italic">That is all I have to say about that! - Forest Gump</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
