				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Just to weigh in - starvation (or more likely, dehydration) is a pretty freaking sucky way to go.  Of course, without any sort of higher brain functions, she'll never know.
<br />

<br />
Seriously. It's been FIFTEEN YEARS.  She's -not- going to get better.  Let her GO.
<br />

<br />
For those who are criticizing the law, how would -you- write it?  Maybe you'd have given control to her parents?  Well, what if it was her parents who thought it would be right to just let her die?  Would you then be arguing the other way?   It doesn't -matter- which person the law elects as the legal next of kin as long as it makes some modicum of sense (You could argue that one's spouse is more likely to still be around to make the decision than one's parents.).  you've got to pick SOMEONE, and then you need to follow through.
<br />

<br />
I personally find the idea of my loved ones wasting money on keeping my braindead body alive for 15 years repulsive.  Take that money and have a few parties in my honor or something.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
