			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I live where this is happening. It is on the front page, the 2nd page, the Metro/State section, these people are my neighbors, co-workers, friends, enemies and representatives in government. I've read every article on the topic, every interview, report, etc. for many years.
<br />

<br />
Several things:
<br />

<br />
The law in this case says Terri Schiavo's next-of-kin is her marital spouse..period. Not the court, not DCFS, not the lawyers, and not her parents..her husband. The original testimony from many years ago has been lost in the legal shuffling and wrangling, but essentially both sides agreed that Mrs. Schiavo did not want to be artificially kept alive. The court has tried to interfere in a marriage and if it were for any other reason but the highly publicised T. Schiavo case, the entire country would be outraged.
<br />

<br />
Mr. Schiavo will gain nothing from her death. The life insurance has long since been spent on attorneys fees and medical bills. Trust me, in this case..he has been investigated every which way and there is absolutely NO evidence of foul play. Two separate people that I'm aware of, have offered him money..one offered 10 million, the other offered 1 million for him to walk away. He declined their offers. I believe he is doing this for moral reasons, she didn't want it - he is doing his best to honor her wishes. Obviously, its not so he can have another relationship..he has one, one which is working and his partner seems content without a marriage contract. I can't blame him on that, its been 15 years after all.
<br />

<br />
Medically, she has no brain left. There is NO bloodflow to her braincells and after an extremely short time of this, those cells die. She is NOT in a coma, she is brain dead. A comotose person doesn't respond, there are no reflexes acting, but there IS brain activity. However, T. Schiavo is awake and has reflexive actions but absolutely NO brain activity whatsoever. This is NOT curable or fixable. She's not going to suddenly wake up and start talking like some comatose people do, because SHE'S NOT IN A COMA. 
<br />

<br />
Removing a feeding tube may seem cruel and you may think her death will be agonizing. Honestly, it won't be. Most people who can still function but whose time has come, simply stop eating and drinking. Then they slip away quietly and peacefully (I've worked in a nursing home and witnessed this as well has had an aging family member do this). Some quotes are below from todays St. Petersburg Times (local newspaper) on this very topic. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Both our fathers died of cancer at home with the help of hospice. Even after days of not eating and little drinking they did not ask for food or fluids when they rallied for brief periods.
<br />

<br />
While there are many who believe that denying food and water to someone near the end of life is painful and cruel, quite the opposite is true. This is a very natural way for our bodies to shut down when we are near death. Natural brain chemicals kick in, and we peacefully pass on to our afterlife, where there is no medicine or pain.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I can assure those doubters out there, fearing that Mrs. Schiavo will suffer, that it does not happen, especially in individuals who have no cognizant awareness - the body produces endorphins in this state that act as a natural anesthetic. My father did not suffer in his last hours and peacefully passed away at home in his own bed, four years ago. In all that time, I have never once felt like a murderer or that my family should have made another decision.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
One last thing..if the law should be changed..changed to what? Should I not have the power to decide this if it were my minor child/baby (I'm 6 months pregnant). What if I were comatose? My husband with whom I've discussed this countless times should NOT be able to carry out my wishes? Instead, the court or my *$%$ mother, who hasn't a clue of my wishes would have that right?
<br />

<br />

<br />
Stormieweather<br />_________________<br />Everytime I close the door on reality, it comes in the window.
