<br />

<br />
I believe it does. I think she it's very possible she didn't tell her parents about her wishes because it would upset them considering their religious views. It's not uncommon to leave such things unsaid or to even embellish but tell others differently in private - like your next of kin. I have no reason to disbelieve the husband in this case. Many people would want to die in Terry's situation and it's a very plausible situation - and by default the husband is next of kin. 
<br />

<br />
Terry will never make a decision again in her life, and her decision to leave her husband as next of kin should simply be respected as it's not the place of goverment to legislate morality, but to facilitate the wishes of it's people. A next of kin is required, so a default has to be set - and that person is chosen for a reason. The relationship I have with my wife is much more intimate then the relationship I have with my parents and she's the one I'd want taking care of my affairs if this happened to me. Plus it's much longer term since most likely my parents will die before she does. It's not a choice they just pulled out of a hat - people really do want their spouse carrying out their wishes as next of kin often and for many reasons. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">One of two things, either he has been trying to 'pull the plug' for the past 15 years, and the parents have been fighting it the whole time....which makes 'after such a long time' inaccurate. Or, he just recently decided to pursue this course of action, the parents fight it, and it lends more doubt as to his motivation for 'carrying out her wishes'. The whole thing wreaks of BS, and it seems to me that someone along the line woulda said "Hey let's err on the side of life rather than death", especially since we really have no idea what her real wishes are, except his word for it.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
For the first four years after the heart attack the Micheal and the family worked together to try and revive Terry without any success. In 1993 they managed to settle their malpractice claims for a million dollars, 5 years later Micheal filed for the tube to be removed. That's 8 years he waited - and 5 years after they found out that she wasn't going to recover. The first ruling took them till 2000, that's 10 years after her injury. Considering how long it took the legal fight from just to get the settlement to largely pay for her therapy and the hope she would recover he took a short period of time to give the parents to grieve - 5 years and then decided it's time to go. People don't always make the most objective choices the day after their loved one suffers a serious brain injury. It doesn't seem like BS to me, it seems like due diligence for the person he loved and her wishes. 
<br />

<br />
Here is a question - why would he spend all this money on legal costs, and subject himself to death threats and horrible media attention if he wasn't doing what he felt was right? Why would he ruin his life when he could have easily just let the parents take care of her?<br />_________________<br />()()
