				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Like I said, all the debate about the morality issues, and all the actions taken by everyone beyond the husband and the parents is all just more crap for people to argue about.
<br />

<br />
My problem with the situation comes down to two basic issues. One, that his justification for arriving in his decision is based on something he claims she confessed to him, and him alone. We have no way of knowing what her true wishes are (were), and I have seen enough inconsistances in his actions to at least question a) whether it really was something she told him and b) what his real motivation is.
<br />

<br />
Second is with the law that enables him to make this decision. You have two extremes when evaluating the state of health of a person. On one side you have people who are either so severely injured or terminally ill that the body ceases to function on its own. This is an obvious case for allowing someone to make the decision to pull the plug. On the other hand, you may have someone injured in an accident where they are expecting a full recovery. Obviously, in that case, they would never let anyone make a decision to end their life. Somewhere in the middle of that is the line where it goes from "no way" to "it's ok". I believe this case fits smack dab on thet gray line because the law is not specific enough.
<br />

<br />
All this is moot now. The parents last chance has been exhausted, and she will die. Once again, I just pray that it really is her wish, because her husband is getting his.<br />_________________<br /><span style="font-style: italic">That is all I have to say about that! - Forest Gump</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
