			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">A local call-in radio show devoted a lot of time to the Schiavo debate this week.  It was very interesting.
<br />

<br />
3 things can happen when you go into a coma.  You may wake up.  You may never wake up.  You may enter a persistent vegetative state.  This last possibility is rare, and unfortunately extremely frustrating for both physicians and most especially loved ones.
<br />

<br />
The medical diagnosis of being a "vegetable" is very time consuming.  Brain scans via MRI and CT are done.  Beyond this imperical data, a neurologist personally interviews and observes the patient.  Because the brain stem alone can elicit responses to stimuli (eyes blinking closing for bright lights, head turning in response to sound - or both happening for no reason at all), it's a difficult job that is done very carefully.
<br />

<br />
The thing medical science knows about this state of undeath is that the brain stem continues to function (eyes blink, heart beats, lung breathe) while all cognitive functions have ceased.  Very few patients show any improvement from such a condition.  As time goes on, the chance for any improvement diminishes.
<br />

<br />
A doctor on the radio show I mentioned stated that after 2 years in such a state, improvement has never been documented by science.  As others have noted about Ms. Schiavo, it's been 15 years.  It's unfortunate her parents don't want to let her go.  
<br />

<br />
Overall, I think our country will benefit from the experience.  More people will create living wills, and more people will be apt to discuss laws such as Oregon's assisted suicide law.  Someday, we may even craft legislation guaranteeing people a right to die in dignity.
<br />

<br />
One thing last week did disturb me greatly.  It was when congress passed, and our President signed a law giving Ms. Schiavo's parents a right to bring their case to a federal court.  The same right wasn't given to everyone in similar circumstances, it was only granted to Ms. Schiavo's parents.  
<br />

<br />
I believe the US is, and should remain, a nation of laws - not individuals.  Singling out people for special rights, or excluding someone from a right others have - that's something I would expect in Saudi Arabia or another Monarchy / Oligarchy.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
